<HEADLINE>
FT  12 JUN 92 / UK Company News: Oxford Instruments shares tumble on 29%
fall
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PEGGY HOLLINGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SHARES in Oxford Instruments underperformed a declining market by tumbling
10 per cent to 229p, as the advanced instrumentation company revealed a
sharper-than-expected 29 per cent fall in profits.
The pre-tax return of Pounds 8.6m for the year to March 29, struck on sales
5 per cent lower at Pounds 103.3m, was about Pounds 1m lower than analysts
had expected. Losses estimated at about Pounds 3m at three subsidiaries were
believed to have been responsible.
Mr Peter Williams, chairman and chief executive, held out little hope for an
improvement in the current year, saying that new orders were about 17 per
cent down to Pounds 95m on the previous year. He added, however, that the
decline appeared to have bottomed out and two of the three subsidiaries were
expected to return to the black this year.
The dividend is raised to 2.9p for a total of 4.3p (4.15p). Earnings per
share fell to 14.7p (16.8p).
The good news came from Oxford's joint venture with Siemens in magnetic body
scanners, which increased its profits contribution by 44 per cent to Pounds
5.1m. This was due to an increased share of a market which was largely
static, Mr Williams said.
Profits were also helped by the Pounds 1.2m tax benefit on the release of
provisions relating to asset disposals in 1991. The tax charge fell from
Pounds 3.99m to Pounds 1.45m.
Mr Williams stressed the continuing importance of research to Oxford
Instruments. The group spent Pounds 8.1m on research and development,
roughly equivalent to last year.
COMMENT
Oxford enjoys a roller coaster relationship with City sentiments: sometimes
up, sometimes down. Yesterday's results sent it hurtling towards earth. For
a start, Oxford's great hope, the synchrotron, may be working very well but
it has no orders for new ones; and the longer it has to wait for an an
economic upturn, the more chance competitors have to catch up. Furthermore,
the lead times are long and the semiconductor market is still flat on its
back. On the brighter side, the cash position is very strong and a lot of
work has been done to rein in costs without damaging research. Also, Oxford
enjoys a healthy lead in some interesting technical areas. But any recovery
will long term. Forecasts are for Pounds 8.5m, with a prospective p/e of
about 20 times. This is not a company for amateurs and certainly not for
short-termers.
</TEXT>
