<HEADLINE>
FT  12 JUN 92 / Kalon in hostile bid for paints rival
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER PEARSE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
KALON GROUP, the West Yorkshire-based paint manufacturer, yesterday launched
a hostile Pounds 106.1m bid for Manders (Holdings), the Wolverhampton
paints, inks and property group.
The eight-for-three all-paper offer values each ordinary Manders share at
about 288p. Manders' shares closed up 54p at 291p while Kalon's fell 2 1/2 p
to 108p.
Mr Mike Hennessy, Kalon managing director, said the offer price represented
a 24 per cent premium to the Manders closing price on Wednesday June 10.
He said Manders was an 'underperforming manufacturing business', though it
also owned the Mander Centre, worth Pounds 57.5m, in Wolverhampton. The
combination of Manders' activities had been 'unsuccessful'. Since 1987 it
had spent more than Pounds 23m on acquisitions, but 1991 pre-tax profits at
Pounds 6.04m compared with Pounds 6.12 in 1988. Manders' shareholders had
suffered, he said. The offer would allow them to benefit from Kalon's
management strengths.
Mr Roy Amos, Manders chairman, said the news of yesterday's bid had 'come
out of the blue', adding that the last contact between the two rivals had
been five years ago when Manders had bid for Kalon.
He described Kalon's move as 'opportunistic' in the light of the current
strength of its share price. The 'unsolicited' offer undervalued Manders,
which was in a 'major transitional period'. He added that the bid was 'not
in anyone's interest, not the employees, not the customers, not the
shareholders'.
Kalon said the two groups had complementary paints businesses, and expected
the enlarged group to have turnover of Pounds 200m. Mr Hennessy envisaged
closing one of the enlarged group's four factories - Windeck in Bingley -
and reducing the combined workforce by 20 per cent.
Kalon was formed in 1985 by the merger of Leyland Paint &amp; Wallpaper with a
private paint company and brought in Mr Hennessy in 1988 to oversee its
reorganisation. In 1988 pre-tax profits were Pounds 3.72m; in 1991 they were
Pounds 9.2m, a growth rate of 36 per cent a year. Over the past four years
Kalon's share price has risen 140 per cent relative to the FT-A All-Share
Index.
Observer, Page 19
</TEXT>
