<HEADLINE>
FT  12 JUN 92 / Help sought in tracing Maxwell funds
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ACCOUNTANTS trying to trace the assets of the late Robert Maxwell yesterday
called on the government to put diplomatic pressure on Liechtenstein and
Switzerland to help unlock information held in secretive foreign trusts.
Mr Peter Phillips, a partner with accountancy firm Buchler Phillips and
receiver to Mr Maxwell's personal estate, said he needed high-level support
to identify funds held in more than a dozen trusts in several countries.
Mr Phillips, who has traced up to Pounds 10m of Mr Maxwell's assets, said:
'Now the government has started using words like crime and fraud in relation
to the Maxwell case, it should come out of its shell and offer help to
groups trying to recover assets.'
His views reflect the concerns of others searching for assets stolen from
pensioners and creditors to the Maxwell empire who have found their work
blocked by regulations to maintain secrecy.
They believe that substantial assets may have been either channelled
through, or be currently placed in, offshore trusts which are refusing to
co-operate.
Mr Neil Cooper, the partner at accountancy firm Robson Rhodes who is
liquidator of Bishopsgate Investment Management - manager and trustee of the
Maxwell pension funds - said he had been offered no assistance from the
government in his search.
'We need jurisdictions overseas to recognise the special nature of this
case, in which we are tracing stolen assets,' he said. 'That sets it aside
from the normal secrecy and privacy conditions by which these countries
operate.'
He said investigators had no sense of the total value of assets which may
have been held in offshore trusts, and had not been able to see their
accounts or interview their directors.
Other accountants attempting to trace assets include partners at Arthur
Andersen, administrators to more than 400 companies in the private Maxwell
business empire.
The government said it would provide help to those tracing Maxwell assets
through a special unit, the creation of which Mr Peter Lilley, social
security secretary, announced in the Commons on Monday.
The Department of Social Security said it would hold discussions with anyone
able to assist in returning stolen assets either in the UK or abroad.
It saw no need to involve the Foreign Office in diplomatic discussions. The
unit is expected to be operating within a few days, and is currently
assembling civil servants and private sector employees to work in it.
The appointment of a chairman drawn from the private sector with financial
experience is expected to be announced early next week.
Mr Cooper said: 'We wait to see if the government is prepared to extend the
channels being proposed to put pressure on banks and institutions to other
institutions and to other states. We would welcome any assistance that could
be given.'
The assets identified by Mr Phillips includes about Pounds 3m from a
Frankfurt office building sold earlier this year and traced to a bank
account in France.
NatWest had doubts on shares; MPs' campaign, Page 8
</TEXT>
