<DATE>920612
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  12 JUN 92 / Parliament and Politics: 'Red route' network to be widened
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE government yesterday announced plans for a 300-mile network of 'red
routes' for London, designed to improve traffic flow in the capital.
Mr Steve Norris, junior transport minister, told the Commons of proposals
for the schemes after 18-month pilot projects in north and east London.
The announcement could pave the way for similar plans in other cities, with
Birmingham, Belfast, Hull and Leeds studying the capital's trials. Edinburgh
is also understood to be interested.
Red routes, officially known as priority routes, curb stopping by vehicles
to allow easy passage for through traffic. Restricted areas are shown by
prominent red kerbside markings and 'no stopping' lines.
Fears that businesses will suffer through the extension of the red route
network were discounted by Mr Norris.
His view was strongly disputed by Labour MPs representing constituencies in
north and east London, and questioned by Mr Peter Brooke, Tory MP for City
of London and Westminster south and a former cabinet minister.
Mr Norris insisted that there was 'no demonstrable link whatever' between
red routes and reduction in business for local shops and other
establishments.
Mr Brooke said: 'The perception of my constituency is very much in the
opposite direction.' He called for an assurance that, if necessary,
amendments would be made to the roads designated as red routes.
Mr Norris promised that 'if the department is wrong it will change its
mind'.
He accused some Labour critics of persisting with tactics that had been
employed during the general election, when the issue of red routes was used
'as a stick to beat Conservative candidates'.
Highlighting the benefits he said had been revealed by the pilot scheme, Mr
Norris added that overall journey times had improved by 25 per cent, while
road casualties fell by more than 200 in 1991 - a fall of some 36 per cent
compared with 12 per cent in London as a whole.
Mr Norris stressed that the journey times of buses had been cut by more than
10 per cent and their reliability improved by a third, resulting in wider
use of them.
Dealing with the traffic problems in the centre of London, he explained that
initially the designated red route would be virtually confined to the inner
ring road, roughly encompassing the area around the main railway stations.
As traffic using Tower Bridge, which formed part of the inner ring road, was
subject to a weight restriction a route via London Bridge would also be
designated.
Mr Norris said the main objectives in the centre of London were to help the
movement of buses and local commercial traffic rather than to serve
longer-distance movements.
He expected the first of the new red routes to be in operation by the end of
next year.
Road traffic increased by 1 per cent in the first quarter of this year
compared with the same period of 1991, according to figures issued yesterday
by the Department of Transport. However, the increase was mainly due to the
leap-year quarter being one day longer.
</TEXT>
