<HEADLINE>
FT  12 JUN 92 / Parliament and Politics: Labour row on votes for shadow team
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A SPATE of claims and counter-claims about past practices in shadow cabinet
elections broke out in the Labour party yesterday as a move developed to
change the voting arrangements for next month's shadow cabinet elections.
Mr Ron Davies, MP for Caerphilly, said that there was a very clear
suggestion that on some occasions the ballot box had been opened and votes
counted before the close of the poll.
'Now if that happens and you have knowledge of the placing of candidates and
you also have in your possession a number of ballot papers, then obviously
you are well placed to affect in a very clear and a very direct way the
outcome of the election,' he said on BBC Radio.
Mr Bryan Gould, a shadow cabinet member and contender for the Labour
leadership, said yesterday that there were sufficient grounds for an inquiry
into the claims.
He said that he had never taken part in deals or been involved in such
activity, but that anyone who had been involved in shadow cabinet elections
in recent years, would know 'that blank ballot papers are in the possession
of some campaign managers'.
Mr Ray Powell, a senior Labour whip, said that on previous occasions some
MPs had given him blank ballot papers so that he could exercise proxy votes
on their behalf, but that these had to be used to support their chosen
candidates.
He vigorously denied that there was any need for an inquiry, and added: 'For
anybody to suggest or imply that any member of parliament would give licence
to any other MP to use his discretion as to how he should vote or she should
vote is absolutely ridiculous.'
Mr Jeff Rooker, MP for Perry Bar, has written to shadow cabinet members
urging that forthcoming party elections are scrutinised by an outside body.
The matter is likely to be raised at a meeting of the parliamentary party
next week or the week after.
But the official party line was that when substantial allegations were made,
they would be examined by the shadow cabinet and officers of the
parliamentary party.
While some in the official camp were accusing their colleagues of raising
the issue in order to gain publicity for their own shadow cabinet election
chances, there is also some concern among MPs that senior frontbenchers who
are supporting Mr Gould in the leadership contest should not find themselves
unfairly penalised.
The shadow cabinet elections overlap with the leadership elections:
nominations close on 16 July - just two days before the leadership vote -
but the ballot does not close until 23 July.
</TEXT>
