<HEADLINE>
FT  12 JUN 92 / Parliament and Politics: Blair claims survey shows cuts in
training provision
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
UP TO 60,000 school-leavers could find themselves without Youth Training
scheme places in the coming months in spite of government guarantees that
all young people would be provided for, the Labour party claimed yesterday .
A survey of the 82 Training and Enterprise Councils carried out by Labour
showed that, in real terms, the YT budget was being cut by Pounds 50m or 7
per cent in the current year, said Mr Tony Blair, shadow employment
secretary.
In addition, the budget for Employment Training for adults was being cut by
Pounds 65m, or over 15 per cent, even though unemployment was continuing to
rise, he said.
Mr Blair challenged the government to 'confirm or deny' the figures and to
explain why ministers 'have consistently denied that cuts are taking place
and that waiting lists exist, when the evidence that we have uncovered
proves precisely the opposite'.
Mr Patrick McLoughlin, employment minister, said the guarantee of YT
provision was being met 'broadly speaking' and that funding this year was
also 'broadly in line' with last year's allocations, in spite of more young
people staying on at school.
The government would discuss with individual Tecs any problems about funding
or meeting the guarantee, said Mr McLoughlin. He added that some waiting
lists were largely administrative because some courses started only at
particular times of the year.
Sixty out of the 82 Tecs replied to Labour's survey. London Tecs are still
negotiating over funding.
