<HEADLINE>
FT  12 JUN 92 / First round of MPs' campaign seen as a success
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MPS YESTERDAY welcomed the first signs of major contributions to help the
Maxwell pensioners. While the moves may relieve some of the immediate
pressure, the government will face a renewed debate on its own
responsibility when the self-critical report by the Investment Management
Regulatory Organisation on the affair is published.
That report is expected shortly - almost certainly before the next meeting
of the 100-strong all-party group of MPs campaigning on behalf of the
Maxwell pensioners, which is likely to re-assemble in about a month. The
report will reinforce the pressure on the government to contribute to
longer-term help for the pensioners.
Mr Richard Page, the group's Tory co-chairman, said he hoped the moves had
'set the trend we hope others will quickly follow'. Mr Tony Newton, leader
of the House, hailed the reports of the possible contribution as a
'substantial vindication of the effective package' of measures to help the
pensioners announced by Mr Peter Lilley, the social security secretary, on
Monday.
The first round of the campaign at Westminster on behalf of the pensioners
has been a victory for backbenchers that has left the front benches looking
slightly flat-footed.
Mr Michael Meacher, shadow social security secretary, did increase the
pressure on the government that began with Monday's lobby of parliament by
Maxwell pensioners, by arranging a debate for Tuesday. However, he became a
victim of his own success, as Mr Lilley's statement did enough of what the
campaign had been seeking to keep the government and its backbenchers on the
same side. The adoption of the measures - as urged by the all-party group -
seemed more a tribute to the campaign, which held its first meeting less
than two months ago, than to Mr Lilley.
Even MPs who were publicly grateful said privately that Mr Lilley could have
engineered a larger headline figure for the temporary grants. But above all
they said that the announcement should have come noticeably before Monday's
lobby as it was inevitably seen as a response.
With the government's need to ensure the credibility of occupational pension
schemes; and a strong report from the cross-party social security committee
in the last parliament, the campaign started with good prospects.
The Labour co-chairman of the group was Mr Frank Field who led the social
security committee in the previous parliament and is widely respected for
his knowledge of this area. Mr Page has kept a lower profile, but has shown
considerable skill as a Westminster fixer.
He contributed to the campaign's success by realistically pitching the first
demands at a 'drip feed' of money for the pension schemes and other measures
that ministers could bring themselves to accept at a time when writing a
taxpayers' cheque for much of the bill was still unthinkable for the
government.
The campaigning MPs will have to decide whether the unthinkable should
become their aim.
</TEXT>
