<HEADLINE>
FT  12 JUN 92 / Anger at suggestion of 'moral obligation'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, ANDREW JACK and ROBERT PESTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BANKS and professional advisers to the Maxwell empire yesterday reacted with
indignation to the suggestion that they have a moral obligation to help
pensioners.
However the National Association of Pension Funds, the industry trade
association, said yesterday that it will be the first to contribute to the
government's voluntary trust fund to aid the Maxwell pensioners with a
donation of Pounds 120,000 - a fraction of the hundreds of millions of
pounds that the pension funds will require.
Mr Peter Lilley, social security secretary, announced on Monday the setting
up of the voluntary trust into which financial institutions that had
'profited handsomely' from dealings with Maxwell companies 'might feel some
moral obligation' to contribute.
Ministers have been privately suggesting for months that both the pensions
industry and the City financial institutions which had dealings with the
late Robert Maxwell might help replace the pensioners' stolen funds.
But the Financial Times yesterday contacted many of the institutions that
did business with the Maxwell empire and found only one which said it would
contribute to a voluntary fund - National Westminster Bank, which holds
shares claimed by the pension funds.
The chief executive of one large City bank said: 'It is out of the question
that City institutions should dig in their pockets to help the pensioners.
It is not our responsibility. The government has already damaged the
reputation of the City internationally by suggesting there should be a
begging bowl to help the pensioners.' He said that it was unlikely that any
voluntary scheme to raise money from the City would work.
Some City institutions regard the plight of the Maxwell pensioners as a
problem which should be solved by the pensions industry. However the
association has made clear that its members will not pick up the tab for the
whole of the deficit.
Mr Paddy Linekar, chief executive of M&amp;G Group, the fund managers, and
chairman of the Institutional Fund Managers Association, said the
association's view was that, while there was great sympathy for the
pensioners' plight, it was up to individual members to decide whether to
contribute. 'But speaking from M&amp;G's point of view, we wouldn't touch
Maxwell with a barge-pole, and it seems a bit rich to ask us to cough up
money.'
Professional advisers to the Maxwell company pension schemes reacted with
equal outrage at the suggestion that they aid pensioners. One adviser to the
Maxwell pension schemes said: 'What about asking the people who clean the
toilets at the Maxwell companies to contribute? After all, they benefited
too. We were no different than they are.'
</TEXT>
