FT  12 JUN 92 / Ruling today on BCCI pay-off
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
SIR DONALD NICHOLLS, the vice-chancellor, will rule in the High Court today
on whether the Pounds 930m settlement negotiated by liquidators of the
collapsed Bank of Credit and Commerce International can go ahead.
Touche Ross, the liquidator, is asking Sir Donald to give the go-ahead for
the deal to be offered to creditors. The deal, which is estimated to give
creditors a return of 30 per cent to 40 per cent, involves the injection of
about Pounds 930m by the Abu Dhabi authorities - the bank's majority
shareholders.
Abu Dhabi yesterday said it had lowered the level of acceptances necessary
for the scheme to go ahead from Dollars 7bn of creditors to Dollars 4.75bn.
The creditors are likely to seek international government help to make good
their losses if the judgment today goes against them.
The package also needs approval from courts in Luxembourg and the Cayman
Islands at hearings later this month.
