<HEADLINE>
FT  12 JUN 92 / The Earth Summit: Tear gas disrupts Bush speech in Panama
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PANAMA CITY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
President George Bush, his eyes watering, was forced to flee a crowded city
square yesterday when riot police fired tear gas to break up a protest
against his 1989 invasion of Panama, Reuter reports from Panama City.
Pandemonium broke out at Plaza Porras, forcing Mr Bush and his wife Barbara
to flee to the safety of their limousine as security men, crouched and
weapons drawn, guarded their exit.
Mr Bush had been scheduled to deliver a speech saluting Panama's return to
democracy in his first visit to the country since US troops invaded in
December 1989 and toppled strongman Manuel Noriega.
Several hundred demonstrators, kept a block away from the square by a line
of riot police, hurled rocks and bottles. Riot police responded quickly by
firing tear gas canisters but the wind blew fumes over the crowd of several
thousand.
Panicked, they surged towards the platform, apparently to escape the noxious
fumes. The gas wafted over the platform where the Bushes and Panamanian
President Guillermo Endara were seated.
US officials said Mr Bush did not suffer injury. He was later seen with
reddened, swollen eyes.
Mr Bush had stopped in Panama for a four-hour visit and later left for the
Earth Summit in Rio de Janeiro.
</TEXT>
