<HEADLINE>
FT  12 JUN 92 / Chauffeurs driven off the road
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM BURT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HOME, James. And don't bother to come back tomorrow.
More than 1,000 uniformed drivers are looking for work in London alone,
according to Britain's leading domestic staff agencies. Demand for
chauffeurs has collapsed to a five-year low as companies and private
individuals cut spending, and there is no sign of an upturn this year.
During the mid-1980s, demand for chauffeurs outstripped supply and top
drivers could command salaries of Pounds 30,000. Since then hundreds of
drivers have been made redundant and salaries have fallen by up to 60 per
cent.
'Company chairmen say the chauffeur is always the first to go,' said Mrs May
Prosser, director of the Beauchamp Bureau. The agency has 200 unemployed
chauffeurs on its books, including the late Mr Robert Maxwell's two drivers.
It found work for only four chauffeurs last year.
Another agency, Hyde Park International, has 575 drivers looking for work
and director Ms Jenny Harrison said: 'We're not placing any at all.'
Masseys, Britain's oldest domestic staff agency, has told chauffeurs not to
register. 'We've got no jobs for them and we haven't seen any increase in
demand,' said Mr Richard Hewitt, managing director.
The All England Club is offering a brief respite to the downturn by
advertising for 216 drivers to ferry players to the Wimbledon tennis
championships later this month. More than 1,000 have applied for two-week
contracts, including two former drivers from Buckingham Palace.
Some ministerial drivers may also be looking for work following the
government's decision to explore contracting out of departmental services.
The Welsh Office yesterday confirmed it was looking at cost savings on the
two chauffeur-driven cars kept in Cardiff. But the Department of the
Environment says the 145 drivers employed by Whitehall are unlikely to be
privatised.
Mr Eric James, a London-based chauffeur, is gloomy about job competition. He
has been unemployed since the Gulf war when his Kuwaiti employers decided
they could no longer afford a personal driver for their Jaguar XJS, BMW and
Mercedes. 'Everyone is cutting back and I don't expect to get any work in
the near future,' he said. 'Chauffeurs are being driven off the road.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 1
