<HEADLINE>
FT  12 JUN 92 / International Company News: Air Russia set-up costs to be
Dollars 900m, says BA
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL BETTS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BERLIN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH AIRWAYS expects the development of Air Russia, its new Moscow-based
joint airline venture, to cost up to Dollars 900m, Sir Colin Marshall, BA
chief executive, said yesterday.
The overall investment to set up the airline would include Dollars 100m in
equity, another Dollars 100m in construction costs for a new terminal at
Moscow's Domodedovo airport, and the balance in working capital and aircraft
funding.
BA will hold a 31 per cent stake in the venture with the remaining 69 per
cent held by Russian partners, including the international commercial
division of Aeroflot, the Domodedovo division of Aeroflot, and the Russian
Republican Innovation Fund.
Sir Colin, speaking at an FT aerospace conference in Berlin, said Air Russia
was expected to start operations in 1994, or possibly earlier.
The new venture would create about 1,000 jobs with no more than between 30
to 40 expatriate managers and training personnel, he added.
The airline plans to initially operate a fleet of seven jet aircraft, with
the Boeing 767 the most likely candidate.
Sir Colin said the project had survived the political turmoil following the
break-up of the Soviet Union last year.
The joint venture's newly-constituted board held its first meeting last
January in Moscow.
BA and its Russian partners plan to turn the proposed new terminal at
Domodedovo airport into the base of a new international East-West airline
hub.
The new airline would operate a network of flights from Moscow to western
Europe and North America and another to destinations in the Far East.
Sir Colin said the biggest current problem facing the new venture was a
regulatory one with the new airline requiring its operating licence and
specific route licences.
</TEXT>
