FT  12 JUN 92 / UK Company News: Bertam to purchase three more plantations
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
BERTAM Holdings has announced further acquisitions in line with its policy
of investing in plantation and development land in Malaysia, with a view to
participation in further schemes with Malaysian partners.
It has conditionally agreed to buy Sungkai Estates and Rembia Rubber from
Rowe Evans Investments for Pounds 4.27m cash, and Lendu Rubber Estates from
Lendu Holdings for some Pounds 1.37m cash.
Rowe Evans will use the proceeds to reduce borrowings and focus operations
and expansion in Indonesia, while Lendu intends to focus on agricultural
projects in Australia, particularly in relation to the 81 per cent
investment in Gubbagunyah, southern Queensland.
As Rowe Evans holds 33.65 per cent of Bertam, shareholder approval will be
needed; also the three acquisitions are conditional upon completion of the
disposal of 2,000 acres of Bertam to its joint venture company, expected by
the end of October.
For the time being all three estates will continue to be operated as
plantations. But Bertam intends to exploit the industrial development
potential of Rembia and Lendu, subject to relevant local regulatory
consents.
All three companies also announced results for 1991. Helped chiefly by the
firmer palm oil market, Bertam lifted pre-tax profit to Pounds 1m (Pounds
810,000) on turnover of Pounds 1.24m (Pounds 1.11m). Earnings per share were
3.09p (2.62p) and the dividend is 2.5p (2p).
Also resulting mainly from the oil palm market, Rowe Evans produced sales of
Pounds 3.93m (Pounds 3.49m) and pre-tax profit of Pounds 1.48m (Pounds
1.35m). Earnings per share slipped to 1.85p (2.05p) but the dividend is
again 1p.
There were recovery signs in wool and wheat markets for Lendu. Its turnover
rose to Pounds 525,000 (Pounds 408,000) and its pre-tax deficit was cut to
Pounds 65,000 (Pounds 138,000). Losses per share came to 0.39p (1.08p) and
the dividend is held at 0.3p.
