<HEADLINE>
FT  12 JUN 92 / SFO defeats threat to powers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND HUGHES, Law Courts Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Serious Fraud Office has defeated a High Court ruling that threatened to
limit its investigatory powers.
In an important judgment on the 'right to silence', five law Lords yesterday
upheld the SFO's claim that it has the legal right to continue questioning a
suspect about an offence after he or she is charged with it.
The Lords examined the exceptional powers, given to the SFO by parliament,
that remove from people questioned the right to silence.
The SFO had appealed against a ruling last November on a challenge to its
powers by Mr Wallace Duncan Smith, chairman of Wallace Smith Trust, who has
been charged with fraud involving at least Pounds 97m.
After Mr Smith had been charged and cautioned by the police that he was not
obliged to say anything, he was required by the SFO to answer questions
under section 2 of the 1987 Criminal Justice Act.
The section empowers the SFO to compel a person under investigation to
answer questions or produce documents, under penalty of up to six months in
jail, and/or a fine.
The High Court granted Mr Smith a declaration that before questioning a
person about an offence with which he has been charged the SFO must inform
him that he is not obliged to answer.
Yesterday Lord Mustill said Mr Smith had argued that an SFO investigation,
and therefore its compulsory powers, ended when a person was charged. That
proposition was impossible to sustain, Lord Mustill added. The act gave the
SFO the power to question about 'any matter relevant to the investigation'
and it was unreal to suggest that once a person had been charged there could
no longer be any such relevant matter.
Mr Smith had then argued that the 1987 act must be understood to preserve
the right to silence. But Lord Mustill said statutory interference with that
right was almost as old as the right itself.
The caution the police had to give was not directly linked to the right but
was a development relating to the admissibility of confessions, and once
that was recognised Mr Smith's argument fell away.
The appeal was not concerned with the admissibility at trial of responses to
SFO questions, or with ensuring the responses were voluntary, so there was
no reason to force on the act a qualification with which it had nothing to
do.
Mr George Staple, SFO director, said later that the judgment represented an
important clarification of the SFO's section 2 powers. 'It will enable us to
exercise these powers more widely than we have in the past due to the
uncertainty in the law.'
The whole issue of the right to silence is among the subjects being
considered by the Royal Commission on Criminal Justice, which is due to
report next spring.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 8
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT922-3300</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CFLAVAAQFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920612
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  12 JUN 92 / Growing demand is part of the furniture: Saleroom
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTONY THORNCROFT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A NEO-CLASSICAL bureau plat made by Jean-Francois Leleu in Paris in the
early 1770s sold for Pounds 1.21m at Christie's in London yesterday.
It was part of the collection of Barbara Johnson, who married into the
American baby-powder family. She is selling some furniture to raise money
for commercial projects in her native Poland. In 1981 at Christie's she paid
Pounds 330,000 for the bureau, which carried an estimate yesterday of Pounds
750,000.
The furniture auction underlined the international demand for top-quality
items and raised Pounds 5.67m, with 18 per cent unsold. The Ashburton
cabinet, made by Pietro Piffetti, cabinet maker to the kings of Sardinia,
around 1765, sold for Pounds 770,000. It had been in the Ashburton family
since the mid 19th century but was only recently identified as the work of
the Italian master.
Another important piece from an English stately home, a Louis XV lacquer
commode, which had been at Luton Hoo, Bedfordshire, sold for Pounds 660,000.
A pair of tables stamped MA, the initials of Marie Antoinette, made Pounds
57,200. They were the work of Jean-Georges Robierscky and were probably
supplied to Marie Antoinette in the months after the start of the French
Revolution in 1789.
A Faberge imperial Easter egg, commissioned by Tsar Nicholas II for his wife
Tsarina Alexandra in 1905 to celebrate the birth of his heir, Alexei, sold
for Dollars 3.095m (Pounds 1.74m) at Sotheby's in New York on Wednesday. It
set an auction record for a Faberge egg.
In all, 54 imperial eggs were produced by the workshop of the St Petersburg
jeweller in the 30 years after 1885, but this is only the fifth to appear at
auction in the past 50 years. The last was sold in 1985 to Malcolm Forbes of
Forbes Magazine for Dollars 1.76m. The Forbes collection was one of the
largest of Faberge eggs and there was concern at Sotheby's that his death
last year had removed the biggest enthusiast. But an anonymous buyer has
filled the gap. The price was spot on the Sotheby's estimate.
</TEXT>
