FT  12 JUN 92 / Italy still without a government
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ROME
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PROSPECTS for quick agreement on the formation of Italy's 51st post-war
government faded yesterday when it was announced that President Oscar Luigi
Scalfaro would need more consultations with political leaders, writes Robert
Graham in Rome.
Mr Scalfaro began consultations last Thursday, hoping to be in a position to
ask someone to form a government by the end of this week. However, he has
found the parties in an unprecedented state of disarray, with none of their
leaders offering guidelines acceptable to others.
The president has to nominate a politician capable of mustering a
parliamentary majority in the unprecedented fragmentation of the legislature
following the April 5 general elections. Political commentators yesterday
said the field of potential candidates for the premiership remained wide
open.
