<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUN 92 / International Capital Markets: Procordia privatisation
advisers appointed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SARA WEBB
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE SWEDISH government will today announce the appointment of Enskilda
Securities of Sweden, Goldman Sachs of the US, and SG Warburg of the UK as
the financial advisers for the SKr18bn (Dollars 3.13bn) privatisation of
Procordia, the Swedish pharmaceutical and food group.
Procordia is due to be privatised this autumn as part of the Swedish
centre-right government's substantial privatisation programme. Up to half
the offering will be made available to international investors.
The state and Volvo, the automotive group and largest industrial company in
the country, each owns 42.7 per cent of the voting shares in Procordia.
Earlier this year, Volvo announced plans to merge with Procordia, but its
proposal was rejected by the Swedish government.
The state's stake in Procordia is valued at about SKr18bn at current market
prices. Some bankers have expressed doubts over whether it will be able to
sell it all in one tranche, given that the Swedish stock market has seen new
equity issuance of between SKr10 and SKr12bn a year in recent years.
However, the state is understood to be eager to sell its shareholding in one
big privatisation.
Up to 50 per cent of the shares will be made available to international
equity investors, with Goldman Sachs and SG Warburg acting as joint global
co-ordinators for the offering. Enskilda will be responsible for the Nordic
region.
Goldman Sachs will manage the US tranche, SG Warburg will manage the UK
tranche, and the rest of the offering in Europe and Asia will be split
between the three houses.
Volvo and the state recently agreed to a share exchange whereby Volvo would
increase its voting stake from 42.7 to 45 per cent ahead of the
privatisation.
</TEXT>
