</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Remember the fuss about John Major's clapped-out plane which shuttled him
around central Europe last month? Well, liberal-minded Croats must think he
is a wise, thrifty hero compared with their President, Franjo Tudjman.
Tudjman's sense of importance of a republic which is the size of Wales,
reached new heights when the United Nations, rather reluctantly, decided to
add Croatia's membership to the UN. Slovenia, and war-torn
Bosnia-Hercegovina, joined at the same time.
