<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUN 92 / Parliament and Politics: Labour plays downdivisions on
Europe
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LABOUR yesterday disguised its internal divisions over the Maastricht treaty
by keeping open all its options if the government tries to press ahead with
ratification.
After an at times heated debate at the weekly meeting of the parliamentary
party, MPs voted by an overwhelming show of hands to remit three diverging
proposals on strategy, allowing the shadow cabinet to prepare a new position
for presentation next week.
While the vote risked Conservative charges that Labour is as undecided as
the government on how to react to the Danish referendum result, it served to
maintain an appearance of party unity.
The compromise was widely seen as a short-term tactical victory for the
party leadership, which had initially responded to a demand from Mr Tony
Benn for a British referendum by tabling an ambiguous amendment.
Its wording, drawn up by Mr Gerald Kaufman, the shadow foreign secretary,
argued that while the Maastricht text fell far short of Labour's official
European Community policy on a number of issues, it also embraced many of
its goals.
Rather than indicating a clear strategy, the shadow cabinet's line merely
insisted that it would be 'improper' for parliament to continue the
ratification process until the Community had decided a clear way forward.
In consequence, the leadership's amendment fell a long way short of an
alternative amendment tabled by Mr Peter Hain, the Tribunite MP for Neath.
His proposal, reportedly attracting growing support from many quarters in
the party, criticised the Maastricht accord for its narrowly monetarist
criteria for economic and monetary union and called for outright Labour
opposition to ratification.
Urging support for the leadership's amendment, Mr Neil Kinnock, the party
leader, praised Mr Hain's goals and in an implicit rebuke for Mr Benn argued
that 'the days for semi-detachment' over Europe were over.
He went on to warn that parliamentary realities, including the possibility
that the Maastricht bill will not be resubmitted, meant it was important not
to 'tie the hands of the future leadership', to be elected on July 18.
When Mr David Blunkett, campaign manager for Mr Bryan Gould's leadership
challenge, argued for the remission of all three proposals he won
overwhelming support, although Mr Benn refused to withdraw his referendum
scheme.
Mr Benn insisted after the meeting that his efforts to win party support for
a plebiscite had had 'a good start' and would build before the party
conference.
Mr Hain claimed that while the parliamentary party clearly opposed the
referendum option, it was equally sceptical about the leadership's cautious
tactics. Praising the meeting's outcome as a 'unity position', he
nonetheless argued that the momentum was now gathering behind his stance of
firm opposition to the treaty terms.
Radical Labour party members were pro-European but opposed to a 'bankers'
vision' of Europe, he said.
In Strasbourg this week, Mr John Smith, now all but certain to be the next
Labour leader, appeared to be giving some ground to Mr Gould's position by
emphasising the need for more democratic accountability in the EC.
While repeating his own firm support for Labour's qualified backing for the
Maastricht accord, he also made clear that it should pursue with its sister
socialist parties an economic strategy 'based on sustainable growth and the
highest possible levels of employment.'
Nonetheless, Labour is clearly tiptoeing towards a position where it can
make common cause with the Tory rebels and vote comfortably against the
government without drawing charges of political opportunism. The aim is to
maximise Conservative unease without putting its own unity at risk in the
process.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
