FT  11 JUN 92 / Parliament and Politics: Review of 'cosy' travel facility
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SOME MPs are not taking kindly to the prospect of having their travel
arrangements made by a German-owned tour operator.
It emerged yesterday that the all-party Commons administration committee is
likely to review 'as an early priority' an arrangement whereby the Palace of
Westminster's transport office has been operated exclusively since 1985 by
Thomas Cook.
The travel company was bought from Midland Bank last week for Pounds 200m by
LTU, Germany's third-biggest package tour operator.
Mr Brian Wilson, Labour MP for Cunninghame North, whose written question led
to the statement that a review was on the cards, said the takeover had
prompted the timing of his question. 'It does seem a cosy arrangement,' he
said.
According to Mr Alan Beith, the Liberal Democrat MP who answered on behalf
of the House of Commons Commission in charge of administration, the original
four-year agreement with Thomas Cook had been extended indefinitely, with
the recommendation that the arrangement be 'fully reviewed' within 12 months
of the start of the present parliament. It was expected that the
administration committee would be 'invited to initiate that review as an
early priority'.
Sir Teddy Taylor, Tory MP for Southend East and a prominent Euro-sceptic,
said it was vital that the contract should be placed immediately for public
tender. 'There is always the possibility that a British-owned firm might be
successful,' he said.
