<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUN 92 / Parliament and Politics: Boundary commission test looms for
Kinnock
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR NEIL KINNOCK and the Labour leadership face a backbench revolt over their
plans not to oppose the first stage of the boundary commission legislation
in next Monday's debate.
Last night the shadow cabinet agreed the party should not vote against the
bill next week, but should make its points through amendments at the
committee stage.
The bill sets new statutory deadlines for completing reviews of boundaries
and introduces more frequent studies. That would change constituency
boundaries before the next general election, a move expected to benefit the
Conservatives.
The Labour frontbench argument for not opposing the measure next week is
that there have to be boundary reviews because it is undeniable that the
population has moved. The Opposition's task is to ensure that the
legislation prevents the government from manipulating the process.
Backbench rebels are planning to force a vote on Monday, and may try to
carry out guerrilla tactics in the bill's later stages. Because it counts as
a constitutional measure, the convention is that the government would not
curtail debate, and that the bill would take up the time of the Commons
itself instead of being considered by a committee.
The move comes against a background of discontent from Labour spokesmen and
backbenchers that Opposition parliamentary tactics have not yet proved
particularly effective against the reduced Tory majority of 21.
Some MPs also recall angrily that Labour gave a relatively easy run to the
bill three years ago which extended the voting rights of expatriates.
Labour's estimates put the effect of the boundary commission reports between
a net gain for the party of four seats and a net loss of ten.
Mr John Prescott, a shadow cabinet member and a contender for Labour's
deputy leadership, said: 'Gerrymandering is an ugly word for a very ugly and
anti-democratic manipulation of people's right to a fair election.'
</TEXT>
