<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUN 92 / Government is accused over Hess records
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID MARSH, European Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SENSITIVE information about the abortive peace mission by Rudolf Hess,
Hitler's deputy, to the UK in 1941 is still being witheld by the government,
it was claimed yesterday.
That was in spite of the release yesterday of official records about Hess's
mysterious arrival in Renfrewshire and his subsequent captivity. The issuing
of documents was part of the government's efforts to reduce enduring
official secrecy over Hess's flight to the UK.
The documents included an apparent suicide note addressed to his family in
Germany a month after his arrival. The letter, together with a similar
message to Hitler, was written in June 1941 while Hess was being
interrogated by government and intelligence officials at Mytchett Place near
Aldershot.
Hess's letter to his family - in which he wrote despairingly, 'As I am
forced to end my life' - was confirmed yesterday by his son Mr Wolf-Rudiger
Hess.
The scrawled letters to Hitler and to his family - addressed as 'My Dear
All' - were referred to in a biography of Hess by Mr Peter Padfield that was
published last year. But Mr Padfield confirmed yesterday that this was the
first time the letters themselves and their content had come to light.
The four pages of letters were the only new documents brought to light in
yesterday's release of about 900 pages of microfilmed documents on the Hess
case by the Public Records Office. Other records published yesterday had
already been known to historians for several years, having been released
through other channels.
Mr John Costello, a former television producer who has pioneered research
into Hess's story using Soviet and US archives, complained that the
government was still withholding sensitive material.
Mr Costello said it was 'ludicrous' that information was coming out from the
files of both the US and the former Soviet Union that was still unavailable
in Britain.
Mr Padfield produced evidence in his book, Hess - Flight for the Fuhrer,
that Hess had been the victim of an elaborate decoy plot by British
intelligence. A 'double-cross' team had lured Hess to Britain by nurturing
his hopes of agreeing a deal with supporters of appeasement in the British
establishment.
Of yesterday's documents, Mr Padfield said: 'What is interesting is what is
not there.' He said he was 'quite convinced' that details of the MI6 plot
against Hess were contained in intelligence files separate from the UK
Foreign Office files now being opened to the public. The MI6 files would
remain secret after all the remaining Foreign Office files on Hess were due
to be released in the next few weeks, Mr Padfield said.
Mr Hess junior, speaking from near Munich, maintained his claims that his
father, who died in Spandau fortress in Berlin in 1987, was murdered by the
British authorities.
He called for full disclosure of the circumstances of his father's flight to
Britain. 'This would please the family as well as the historians,' he said.
'If it seems as if the British government is hiding something, this is
negative for Britain.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
