<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUN 92 / More jobs likely to be shed at BAe
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WHITE, Defence Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH AEROSPACE is ex-pected today to announce a further 700 redundancies
in its Dynamics missile division.
Most of the redundancies - about 450 jobs - will be at Stevenage,
Hertfordshire.
The news comes only a week after BAe announced 640 job losses at its
Stevenage space systems facility. The expected measure will bring to almost
6,000 the number of job reductions announced by leading UK defence
contractors since the start of the year.
It is likely to meet hostile reaction from unions after hopes for the
Dynamics division's future were boosted by the award in March of a Pounds
570m Ministry of Defence contract for new air-to-air missiles.
The division had already announced that it was cutting 450 jobs, bringing
its total workforce down to about 6,000. The reductions are largely among
engineering employees.
In addition to the cuts at Stevenage about 150 jobs are expected to go at
BAe's missile manufacturing plant at Lostock, near Bolton, and more than 100
at Bristol.
BAe warned this year that 10,000 jobs would be shed in the group over two
years after preliminary 1991 results showing a pre-tax loss of Pounds 81m.
Mr Tim Webb, national officer of the MSF general technical union, said the
cuts would be 'yet another blow to the reputation of British Aerospace as
Britain's leading manufacturer'.
Meanwhile, unions representing MoD civilian personnel yesterday pressed Mr
Malcolm Rifkind, defence secretary, for a share of defence budget savings to
be paid to staff affected by government cuts.
About 20,000 staff are due to leave under the Options for Change programme.
Over-60s will be compulsorily retired, and 14,000 headquarters staff are to
be relocated outside London.
</TEXT>
