FT  11 JUN 92 / Bank of Scotland bows out of refinancing package
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SENIOR executives of Mirror Group Newspapers have been told that Bank of
Scotland has decided not to go ahead with providing Pounds 30m towards a
refinancing package.
The Bank of Scotland has been banker to the Glasgow-based Scottish Daily
Record and Sunday Mail newspapers for nearly a century. It is understood
that the Daily Record may now consider moving its account to another bank.
Bank of Scotland is one of a consortium of banks negotiating a medium-term
package to provide MGN with greater stability while decisions over its
future are taken. The package is believed to involve a facility of Pounds
250m for two years.
It is particularly important for the Record because new colour presses are
already in Glasgow, but there is insufficient money to install them.
MGN was told that the reason for Bank of Scotland's decision was 'financial
prudence'. Bank of Scotland said last night: 'The bank has not withdrawn
from the consortium, nor has it reduced the limits (of the Scottish Daily
Record).'
National Westminster, the senior consortium bank, has been reallocating the
Pounds 30m among other member banks and it is believed that most of it has
been placed. The refinancing of MGN is not thought to have been jeopardised.
The company is expected to go ahead with the publication of its accounts
later this month. That will be followed soon after by a relisting of its
shares.
Observer, Page 21
