<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUN 92 / Court to settle Maxwell claim
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE, Legal Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NATIONAL Westminster Bank yesterday asked the High Court to settle the
dispute over the ownership of shares in Teva, an Israeli pharmaceutical
company, which are held by the bank as security and are claimed both by the
Maxwell pension funds and by the administrator of Robert Maxwell Group, one
of the Maxwell private companies.
NatWest said if the court decided that beneficial ownership of the shares
never passed from the funds managed by Bishopsgate Investment Management to
RMG, then it was prepared to relinquish the security and return the shares
to the pension funds.
If, however, the court ruled that title in the shares passed from BIM and
the common investment fund to RMG before being mortgaged to the bank in
return for a loan, then it would not return them, because it was a 'bona
fide purchaser for value without notice'.
The 25m Teva shares, with a value of just less than Pounds 20m, were
mortgaged to NatWest as security for a new loan of Dollars 27.3m on November
7 last year after a Maxwell request for new money to meet interest payments
due on the MCC 'jumbo facility' used to fund the purchase of Macmillan.
The bank said the mortgage was taken in good faith after receiving written
assurances that they were beneficially owned by RMG. NatWest asked questions
before accepting the mortgage because the certificates were in the name of
BIM. It then took a mortgage in the same form from BIM as a guarantee for
the RMG mortgage.
NatWest said yesterday it was only on December 5, when the Maxwell private
companies went into administration, that it was notified by the pension fund
managers that the shares might be trust assets.
It asked the court to determine the issue because the RMG administrators
indicated the shares should not be surrendered to the detriment of other RMG
creditors.
</TEXT>
