FT  11 JUN 92 / Danger of UPI closure tomorrow
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By OUR FOREIGN STAFF
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
UNITED Press International, the loss-ridden news agency, last night was in
danger of closure tomorrow, the Rev Pat Robertson, a US television
evangelist who once had presidential ambitions, having decided not to
proceed with his Dollars 6m (Pounds 3.2m) takeover.
He had told a Washington news conference yesterday that a review of UPI's
finances and operations showed 'its economics just don't seem to make
sense'. He said he might bid for one or two of the company's assets,
including possibly its name, later in the day.
Last night, the agency stated that it would cease operations at the end of
tomorrow if additional funds were not found. Lawyers for UPI said the agency
was negotiating with other potential buyers, but the company president
conceded that it faced an uphill battle.
Mr Robertson, who runs the Christian Broadcasting Network, emerged as the
only bidder for all of UPI at a bankruptcy hearing last month. He was given
30 days to inspect its books, during which time he has been paying the 500
staff still working at the agency.
Advisers had told him he would have to spend about Dollars 31m on UPI over
the next 18 months to make it notionally viable, but with no guarantee of
commercial success. He noted wryly that his broadcasting company had
recently dropped UPI's service in favour of Associated Press.
