<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUN 92 / UN paves way for troops in Sarajevo
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUDY DEMPSEY and JUREK MARTIN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BELGRADE, WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A UNITED Nations convoy was attacked in Sarajevo yesterday while on its way
to meet UN military officers who are to prepare the way for 1,000 troops
whose task will be to lift the siege of the city's airport.
Sarajevo radio said one man was injured in the attack on the peace-keeping
convoy before it met up with the officers, who had just arrived on the
outskirts of the city after a day-long drive from Belgrade through
Bosnia-Hercegovina's war zone.
The officers, led by senior peace-keeper General Lewis Mackenzie, hope to
arrange the removal of all anti-aircraft weapons held by Serb irregulars
surrounding the airport and oversee their withdrawal from the immediate
vicinity to allow the transport of supplies for thousands of hungry
residents.
UN officials stressed that the operation 'was highly dangerous' since it
depended on all sides honouring a ceasefire.
'Ceasefires come and go, but we have to keep trying,' said Mr Cedric
Thornberry, the UN's chief negotiator.
The officials also warned that they did not have the means to provide air
cover for the UN troops.
The 1,000 troops, which will be drawn from Canada's Royal 22nd regiment,
will be equipped with 80 armoured personnel carriers to safeguard the flow
of humanitarian relief supplies through the airport into Sarajevo.
In Washington yesterday, a senior US senator warned that military action
might be needed to curb Serbia's territorial ambitions. 'The time for
drawing the line has come,' said Senator Richard Lugar, a Republican from
Indiana.
'The UN should authorise nation states to use force. Nato should draw up
plans for a comprehensive use of force as thorough as that formulated for
air, sea and ground forces in Desert Storm,' he added.
Senator Lugar's intervention is an attempt to end US political indifference
to events in Bosnia-Hercegovina.
No shelter from the storm: Page 20
