<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUN 92 / Major denies cabinet split on Maastricht
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR John Major moved yesterday to quell reports of damaging splits within the
cabinet over the Maastricht treaty.
Mr Peter Lilley, social security secretary and one of the most Euro-sceptic
cabinet ministers, last night released a statement denying he was at odds
with the prime minister over Maastricht.
Speaking in Bogota, Columbia, the prime minister said: 'There is no cabinet
crisis and there is no difference of view whatever among any members of the
cabinet.'
Ministers acknowledged privately, however, that the government is under
pressure from Tory MPs, even in more pro-Europe sections of the party, to
look for greater revisions than it has been prepared to contemplate.
As Labour MPs yesterday voted to keep their options open over tactics on the
Maastricht bill, some Conservatives said the government would be defeated if
the Commons voted on the treaty before the summer recess.
With Mr Douglas Hurd, foreign secretary, in France until Friday and Mr Major
in South America, speculation at Westminster of government rifts and
possible resignations has grown - centred on reports that Mr Lilley and Mr
Michael Portillo, chief secretary to the Treasury, attended a meeting of
Tory Euro-sceptics last week.
Conservative business managers were yesterday warning of 'black propaganda'
by the most radical of Euro-sceptics who, they said, were keen to talk up
the government's dilemma.
So far, the government has hinted at only limited flexibility, in order to
overcome the Danish referendum result. It argues that a renegotiation would
not be to Britain's advantage and could wreck the government's ambitions for
its presidency, which begins on July 1. 'It would be folly to throw away the
gains we have in that treaty rather than building on those gains for the
future,' Mr Major said.
But ministers stressed that the government was playing a waiting game,
pending the outcome of at least the Irish referendum next week and the
Lisbon EC summit at the end of the month. 'All of us are trying to use as
cautious language as possible', one said.
The Foreign Office has already hinted that Britain may try to add an
addendum to the Maastricht treaty reinforcing the principle by which
decisions are made at the lowest appropriate level of government.
Mr Norman Lamont, chancellor of the exchequer, underlined his scepticism
about fast moves towards European union, when he said on BBC radio that: 'We
don't want to see ever more resources being taken from individual countries
and appropriated to the centre. . . We want a looser and a broader Europe.'
European finance ministers agreed public opinion could not be ignored, Mr
Lamont said.
In his statement, Mr Lilley said the deal negotiated by the prime minister
at Maastricht 'gives us a good opportunity to shape Europe in the way we
want'.
Meanwhile, a meeting of the Labour parliamentary party yesterday suggested
growing support for rejecting Maastricht among Labour MPs - although the
party leadership succeeded in presenting the party as unified by postponing
a vote until next week at the earliest.
